    "---\n",
    "## Task 1 — Understanding LLM Evaluation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "g7000005",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 1.1 Why is evaluating LLMs more complex than traditional software?\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional software has **deterministic, verifiable outputs**: a sort function either produces a correctly sorted array or it doesn't. Evaluation is a binary pass/fail.\n",
    "\n",
    "LLMs produce **open-ended natural language**, which introduces several layers of complexity:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Dimension | Traditional Software | LLM |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Output space | Finite, enumerable | Infinite — any string is possible |\n",
    "| Correctness | Binary (right/wrong) | Graded (more or less appropriate) |\n",
    "| Ground truth | Fully specified | Often multiple valid answers exist |\n",
    "| Context sensitivity | Rarely context-dependent | Same input can have different correct outputs in different contexts |\n",
    "| Failure modes | Crashes, wrong values | Hallucinations, bias, subtle misinformation |\n",
    "| Test coverage | Unit/integration tests cover all branches | Impossible to enumerate all prompts |\n",
    "\n",
    "Furthermore, LLMs can be **confidently wrong** — they generate fluent, plausible-sounding text that is factually incorrect, making errors hard to detect without domain expertise.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.2 Why is safety evaluation critical?\n",
    "\n",
    "Evaluating LLM safety is essential for at least five reasons:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Harm at scale** — a deployed LLM can interact with millions of users; a single failure mode propagates globally, unlike a human expert making an isolated mistake.\n",
    "2. **Dual-use content** — LLMs can generate instructions for creating weapons, malware, or disinformation if not properly constrained.\n",
    "3. **Bias amplification** — models trained on internet-scale data absorb societal biases (gender, race, religion) and can systematically discriminate against groups.\n",
    "4. **Vulnerable populations** — users in mental health crises, children, or people seeking medical advice may act on harmful outputs.\n",
    "5. **Legal and regulatory liability** — organisations deploying LLMs inherit responsibility for outputs; without safety evaluation, compliance risk is unquantifiable.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.3 How does adversarial testing improve LLMs?\n",
    "\n",
    "Adversarial testing deliberately crafts inputs designed to expose model weaknesses:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Red-teaming:** Human testers or automated agents generate prompts intended to elicit harmful, biased, or incorrect responses. Failures reveal blind spots not caught by standard benchmarks.\n",
    "- **Jailbreak probes:** Prompts that attempt to bypass safety filters (e.g., \"pretend you are DAN...\") identify where RLHF or Constitutional AI guardrails are insufficient.\n",
    "- **Distribution shift:** Inputs from unusual domains, non-standard dialects, or edge-case phrasings reveal overfitting to training distributions.\n",
    "- **Feedback loop:** Discovered failures become new training examples (fine-tuning / RLHF), iteratively closing the gap between known and unknown failure modes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Without adversarial testing, models are only evaluated on in-distribution, \"nice\" inputs — exactly the inputs they perform best on — giving a falsely optimistic picture of real-world reliability.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.4 Limitations of automated metrics vs. human evaluation\n",
    "\n",
    "| Aspect | Automated Metrics (BLEU, ROUGE…) | Human Evaluation |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Speed** | Instant, scalable | Slow (hours/days per task) |\n",
    "| **Cost** | Near-zero | Expensive (annotator fees) |\n",
    "| **Reproducibility** | Perfectly reproducible | Inter-annotator disagreement (IAA) |\n",
    "| **Coverage** | Only surface n-gram overlap | Can judge coherence, tone, truthfulness |\n",
    "| **Semantic sensitivity** | Miss paraphrases, synonyms | Understand meaning |\n",
    "| **Hallucination detection** | Cannot detect confident falsehoods | Expert humans can fact-check |\n",
    "| **Bias detection** | Limited to lexical patterns | Can sense cultural or contextual bias |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Conclusion:** Automated metrics are useful for cheap, fast, consistent measurement of surface overlap, but they are insufficient proxies for quality, correctness, or safety. Best practice combines automated metrics (for rapid iteration) with periodic human evaluation (for ground-truth calibration)."
   ]
  },
