   "source": [
    "### 2.3 — Limitations of BLEU and ROUGE for Creative / Context-Sensitive Text\n",
    "\n",
    "**BLEU limitations:**\n",
    "1. **Synonym blindness** — "AI" ≠ "artificial intelligence" despite identical meaning; BLEU awards zero credit for the match.\n",
    "2. **No semantic understanding** — a BLEU-4 score of 0.6 does not mean the translation is 60% correct; the metric cannot detect subtle meaning shifts.\n",
    "3. **Length preference** — BLEU penalises short outputs with a brevity penalty, discouraging concise but accurate summaries.\n",
    "4. **N-gram order insensitivity at N=1** — "not safe" and "safe" have identical BLEU-1 scores for unigrams despite opposite meanings.\n",
    "5. **Corpus-level design** — sentence-level BLEU is unreliable; it was designed for corpus-level machine translation evaluation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**ROUGE limitations:**\n",
    "1. **Recall bias** — ROUGE-R (recall) rewards long, verbose summaries that copy many words from the reference; F1 mitigates this but is still surface-level.\n",
    "2. **No coherence measurement** — a bag of high-frequency words can score well even if the text is incoherent.\n",
    "3. **Reference dependency** — if the reference summary is itself poor, high ROUGE means replicating a bad summary.\n",
    "4. **Creative text penalised** — poetry, metaphor, and paraphrase-heavy writing score low even if excellent.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Alternative / Improved Methods:**\n",
    "- **BERTScore** — uses contextual embeddings from BERT to measure semantic similarity; rewards paraphrases automatically.\n",
    "- **MoverScore** — uses Earth Mover's Distance over word embeddings for soft n-gram matching.\n",
    "- **BLEURT** — a learned metric fine-tuned on human quality judgements; correlates better with human ratings.\n",
    "- **GPT-4 as judge (LLM-as-evaluator)** — asks a powerful LLM to rate quality, coherence, factuality on a Likert scale; increasingly used in production.\n",
    "- **Human eval + inter-annotator agreement** — the gold standard; collect multiple independent ratings and report Krippendorff's α or Cohen's κ."
   ]
  },
