   "source": [
    "### 3.3 — What does a perplexity of 100 mean, and how to improve it?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretation:**  \n",
    "A perplexity of **PP = 100** means the model is, on average, as confused as if it had to choose uniformly among **100 equally likely next words** at every step. Equivalently, it assigns an average probability of `1/100 = 0.01` to each correct next token — indicating poor predictive confidence.\n",
    "\n",
    "For context:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Perplexity | Interpretation |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| < 10 | Excellent — model is very confident in next-word prediction |\n",
    "| 10–50 | Good — typical for well-tuned GPT-class models on held-out text |\n",
    "| 50–100 | Moderate — model is uncertain; some domain mismatch |\n",
    "| > 100 | Poor — large distribution mismatch or insufficient training |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Ways to improve from PP=100:**\n",
    "1. **More training data** — larger, more diverse corpora reduce cross-entropy loss.\n",
    "2. **Domain-specific fine-tuning** — if evaluating on medical text, fine-tune on medical corpora; general models have high perplexity on specialised domains.\n",
    "3. **Larger model (scale)** — perplexity drops predictably with model size (Chinchilla scaling laws).\n",
    "4. **Better tokenization** — subword tokenizers (BPE, SentencePiece) reduce vocabulary-mismatch perplexity.\n",
    "5. **Architecture improvements** — longer attention windows (for long-range dependencies), better positional encodings.\n",
    "6. **Data quality** — deduplication and quality filtering (e.g., C4 cleaning) often reduce perplexity more than increasing raw data volume."
   ]
  },
