    "### 6.1 — Which metric is most appropriate for summarisation, and why?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Recommended approach: BERTScore + Human Evaluation (sampled)**\n",
    "\n",
    "For **text summarisation**, the ideal metric must:\n",
    "1. Reward paraphrasing (summaries should not copy verbatim)\n",
    "2. Penalise hallucinations (fabricated facts not present in the source)\n",
    "3. Evaluate faithfulness (does the summary accurately reflect the source?)\n",
    "4. Be affordable enough to run at scale\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why not BLEU?**  \n",
    "BLEU was designed for machine translation, where the output should closely mirror the source. Summarisation is *abstractive* — paraphrasing is desirable, not penalised. BLEU-2/3/4 scores are near-zero for good abstractive summaries.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why ROUGE is the current standard (despite limitations)?**  \n",
    "ROUGE-1/2/L became the field standard partly for historical reasons. They are fast, cheap, and widely adopted, making comparisons across papers straightforward. ROUGE-L correlates better with human judgement than BLEU on summarisation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why BERTScore is better for research?**  \n",
    "BERTScore uses contextual token embeddings — it gives credit for \"automobile\" matching \"car\", and for \"reduce\" matching \"lower\". This better captures the semantic equivalence central to good summarisation. Studies show BERTScore correlates more strongly with human fluency and adequacy ratings than ROUGE.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The practical recommendation:**  \n",
    "- **Development/iteration:** ROUGE-L (fast, cheap, standard)\n",
    "- **Publication/benchmarking:** ROUGE + BERTScore (complementary signal)\n",
    "- **Production quality gate:** Periodic human evaluation (faithfulness, factuality) on a random sample\n",
    "- **Safety-critical applications (healthcare, legal):** Human factuality checking mandatory"
   ]
  },
